15: {
  title: 'Vol Skew & Term Structure — Reading the Market\'s Fear',
  module: 3,
  concept: `
<p><strong>Volatility Skew</strong> is the single most important market signal for a vol trader. It shows you exactly where the market is afraid — and fear creates opportunity.</p>
<h4>What Is Skew?</h4>
<p>If Black-Scholes were perfectly correct, all options on the same stock with the same expiry would have the SAME implied volatility. They don't. Puts typically have higher IV than calls. This is the <strong>skew</strong> (or "smile").</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>OTM puts cost more (higher IV)</strong> → demand for crash protection</li>
<li><strong>OTM calls cost less (lower IV)</strong> → less demand for upside protection</li>
<li><strong>Steeper skew = more fear</strong> → more expensive insurance → more opportunity to sell it</li>
</ul>
<h4>Volatility Term Structure</h4>
<p>IV also varies by expiration date:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Contango (normal):</strong> Near-term IV < Long-term IV. Markets are calm, no immediate fear.</li>
<li><strong>Backwardation (crisis):</strong> Near-term IV > Long-term IV. Immediate fear — people paying up for short-term protection.</li>
</ul>
<p>VIX term structure in backwardation is one of the strongest sell signals: it means panic is priced in, and panic typically mean-reverts fast.</p>
<h4>Why Does Skew Exist? Three Explanations</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Supply/Demand:</strong> Institutional hedgers buy OTM puts (portfolio insurance), driving up put IV. Few people buy OTM calls for protection, so call IV stays lower.</li>
<li><strong>Fat tails:</strong> The market knows returns are negatively skewed with fat tails. Puts SHOULD cost more because the probability of a large down move exceeds what a normal distribution implies. Skew is the market's correction for B-S's wrong distributional assumption.</li>
<li><strong>Leverage effect:</strong> When stocks drop, leverage increases (debt/equity ratio rises), making the company riskier, which increases future vol. This creates a negative correlation between returns and vol — exactly what skew prices in.</li>
</ol>
<h4>SABR and Local Volatility — Beyond B-S</h4>
<p>Professional vol traders don't use flat B-S vol. They use models that explain the smile: <strong>Local Volatility</strong> (Dupire) makes vol a function of strike and time. <strong>SABR</strong> makes vol itself stochastic (vol has its own vol!). These models use the convex optimization techniques from Boyd's textbook to calibrate to market prices — the intersection of math and markets.</p>
  `,
  poker: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Skew = table fear dynamics.</strong> At a poker table, when a tight player 3-bets, everyone gives them credit for a monster. The "implied range" is narrow and strong. That's like steep put skew — everyone assumes the worst.</p>
<p>But if you KNOW the tight player is actually 3-betting wider than the table thinks, you can profitably call (or 4-bet light). You're exploiting the gap between perceived risk and actual risk.</p>
<p>That's exactly what selling put skew does. The market is paying a premium for crash protection (steep skew). If you believe the actual crash risk is lower than what's priced in, selling OTM puts collects that fear premium.</p>
<p><strong>Term structure = tournament stage.</strong> Early levels (far expiry) = calm, low blinds. Bubble (near expiry in crisis) = everyone tightens up, fold equity goes through the roof. The "value" of aggression is highest at the bubble — same as vol selling during backwardation.</p>
</div>
  `,
  formula: `
<div class="formula-title">Skew & Term Structure Metrics</div>
<p><strong>25-delta skew:</strong></p>
<p>$$\\text{Skew}_{25} = IV_{25\\Delta\\,put} - IV_{25\\Delta\\,call}$$</p>
<p>Typical SPY skew: 4-8 vol points. During crises: 15-25 vol points.</p>
<p><strong>Skew ratio:</strong></p>
<p>$$\\text{Skew Ratio} = \\frac{IV_{25\\Delta\\,put}}{IV_{ATM}}$$</p>
<p>Normal: 1.05-1.15. Panicky: 1.20-1.40.</p>
<p><strong>Term structure slope:</strong></p>
<p>$$\\text{Slope} = IV_{90d} - IV_{30d}$$</p>
<p>Positive = contango (normal). Negative = backwardation (crisis/opportunity).</p>
  `,
  example: `
<p><strong>Reading SPY skew right now (from Program 1 output):</strong></p>
<p>Our Program 1 dashboard showed the vol skew for SPY. Typical reading:</p>
<ul>
<li>25Δ put IV: 22%</li>
<li>ATM IV: 18%</li>
<li>25Δ call IV: 16%</li>
<li>Skew = 22% − 16% = <strong>6 vol points</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>This means OTM puts are priced 6 vol points higher than equivalent OTM calls. The market is paying extra for downside insurance. If you believe the actual probability of a crash is lower than what 22% put IV implies, selling those puts is +EV.</p>
<p><strong>Program 1 also showed the term structure:</strong> near-term IV was slightly lower than long-term = <strong>contango = normal market</strong>. No panic, no special opportunity from term structure alone. You'd focus on regular VRP harvesting.</p>
  `,
  problems: [
    { type:'basic', q:'SPY ATM IV is 16%. The 25-delta put has IV=21% and the 25-delta call has IV=14%. (a) What\'s the 25-delta skew? (b) Is this normal, elevated, or extreme? (c) What trade would exploit this if you think skew is too steep?',
      a:'(a) Skew = 21% − 14% = <strong>7 vol points</strong>. (b) <strong>Normal to slightly elevated</strong> (typical range is 4-8). (c) <strong>Sell OTM puts, buy OTM calls</strong> (a "risk reversal" — short the expensive put, long the cheap call). Or simply sell put spreads to harvest the elevated put IV while capping your downside. The steep skew means puts are "expensive" relative to calls.' },
    { type:'jane_street', q:'VIX spot = 28, VIX 30-day future = 24, VIX 90-day future = 22. (a) Is the term structure in contango or backwardation? (b) What does this signal about market conditions? (c) You can sell a VIX put spread (short 28 put, long 22 put) for $3.50. If VIX mean-reverts to 20 within 30 days, what\'s your P&L? What\'s the max loss?',
      a:'(a) <strong>Backwardation</strong> — spot (28) > 30d (24) > 90d (22). Near-term fear exceeds long-term expectations. (b) The market is in <strong>acute stress</strong>. People are panicking and paying up for immediate protection. Historically, VIX backwardation is one of the strongest mean-reversion signals — VIX almost always drops within weeks. (c) If VIX goes to 20: your short 28 put is worth $8 (ITM by 8), your long 22 put is worth $2 (ITM by 2). Spread value = $8−$2 = $6. You sold for $3.50, cost to close = $6. <strong>P&L = −$2.50</strong>. Wait — actually if you\'re SELLING a put spread you\'re SELLING the higher strike put. Let me reconsider: short the 28 put for ~$4.50, long the 22 put for ~$1.00, net credit = $3.50. At VIX=20: short 28 put expires $8 ITM (you owe $8), long 22 put expires $2 ITM (you receive $2). Net loss = $8−$2−$3.50 credit = <strong>$2.50 loss</strong>. Max loss = spread width − credit = $6 − $3.50 = $2.50. The trade was wrong! Better play: sell the VIX CALL spread (short 28 call, long 34 call) to bet on mean-reversion DOWN.' }
  ],
  resources: [
    { title:'Shreve: Volatility Smile', url:'file:///C:/Users/17084/Desktop/Quant Resources/Steve_ShreveStochastic_Calculus_for_Finance_II.pdf', type:'📖 Local PDF', desc:'Why the smile exists mathematically' },
    { title:'CBOE: VIX Term Structure', url:'https://www.cboe.com/tradable_products/vix/vix_term_structure/', type:'Data', desc:'Live VIX futures term structure — check daily' },
    { title:'Convex Optimization Ch. 1', url:'file:///C:/Users/17084/Desktop/Quant Resources/bv_cvxbook.pdf', type:'📖 Local PDF', desc:'Optimization concepts used in vol surface fitting' }
  ]
}

