// ─── ESSENTIALS PAGE ─────────────────────────────────────
function renderEssentials() {
  const sections = [
    {
      num: 1,
      title: 'Expected Value (EV)',
      subtitle: 'The single most important concept in trading',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>EV is the probability-weighted average of all outcomes.</strong> If you take a trade 1,000 times, EV tells you the average result per trade. Positive EV = take it. Negative EV = fold.</p>
<p>$$E[X] = \\sum_{i} x_i \\cdot P(x_i)$$</p>
<p><strong>Linearity of Expectation:</strong> E[X + Y] = E[X] + E[Y], ALWAYS — even when X and Y are correlated. Portfolio EV = sum of individual trade EVs.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Quick Calc</h4><p>EV = P(win) × win_amount + P(loss) × loss_amount</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Poker Analogy</h4><p>Pot odds vs. hand equity. If your equity exceeds the price to call, it's +EV. Same in options.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Why It Matters</h4><p>Every straddle you sell, every iron condor — it's an EV bet. Vol Risk Premium makes selling vol structurally +EV.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 2,
      title: 'Probability Distributions',
      subtitle: 'Normal, log-normal, and fat tails',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Normal Distribution</strong> — Bell curve. Defined by mean (μ) and std dev (σ). ~68% of data within ±1σ, ~95% within ±2σ.</p>
<p><strong>Log-Normal</strong> — Stock prices can't go below zero, so returns are log-normal. This is why Black-Scholes uses log returns.</p>
<p><strong>Fat Tails</strong> — Real markets have fatter tails than normal. Crashes (−20%) happen ~10x more often than normal predicts. This is why risk management matters more than edge size.</p>
<p>$$\\text{Normal PDF: } f(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sigma\\sqrt{2\\pi}} e^{-\\frac{(x-\\mu)^2}{2\\sigma^2}}$$</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>68-95-99.7 Rule</h4><p>±1σ = 68% · ±2σ = 95% · ±3σ = 99.7%. SPY at 1σ move = ATM straddle price ÷ √2.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Kurtosis</h4><p>Normal = 3. Markets ≈ 5-10. Higher = fatter tails = more blowup risk. Always size for fat tails.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 3,
      title: 'Black-Scholes & Greeks',
      subtitle: 'How options are priced and how they move',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Black-Scholes</strong> prices European options using 5 inputs: Stock price (S), Strike (K), Time to expiry (T), Risk-free rate (r), Volatility (σ).</p>
<p>$$C = S \\cdot N(d_1) - K e^{-rT} \\cdot N(d_2)$$</p>
<p>$$d_1 = \\frac{\\ln(S/K) + (r + \\sigma^2/2)T}{\\sigma\\sqrt{T}}, \\quad d_2 = d_1 - \\sigma\\sqrt{T}$$</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Delta (Δ)</h4><p>Direction. How much option price moves per $1 stock move. ATM call ≈ 0.50. Use as probability proxy.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Gamma (Γ)</h4><p>Acceleration. Rate of delta change. Highest ATM near expiry. Gamma = your enemy when short options.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Theta (Θ)</h4><p>Time decay. How much value you lose per day. Negative for longs, positive for shorts. This is your income as a vol seller.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Vega (ν)</h4><p>Vol sensitivity. $/point of IV change. Long options = long vega. Short options = short vega (you want IV to drop).</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Rho (ρ)</h4><p>Rate sensitivity. Usually small. Higher rates benefit calls, hurt puts. Matters more for LEAPS.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 4,
      title: 'IV vs RV — The Structural Edge',
      subtitle: 'The volatility risk premium that pays you every day',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Implied Volatility (IV)</strong> = what the market THINKS vol will be (priced into options).</p>
<p><strong>Realized Volatility (RV)</strong> = what the stock ACTUALLY does (historical measurement).</p>
<p><strong>Vol Risk Premium (VRP) = IV − RV</strong>. This is persistently positive because investors overpay for insurance. It's the single most reliable edge in options trading.</p>
<p>$$\\text{VRP} = IV_{\\text{implied}} - RV_{\\text{realized}} \\approx +3\\text{ to }+5\\text{ vol points on average}$$</p>
<p><strong>Poker translation:</strong> IV vs RV gap = pot odds mispricing. The market consistently overprices uncertainty. Selling vol = being the house.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>When to Sell Vol</h4><p>IV Rank > 50th percentile + VRP positive + no binary events. This is your bread and butter.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>When to Buy Vol</h4><p>IV Rank < 20th percentile + upcoming catalyst (earnings, FOMC). Rare but powerful.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>RV Calculation</h4><p><code>RV = std(log_returns) × √252 × 100</code> — annualized from daily returns.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 5,
      title: 'Kelly Criterion & Position Sizing',
      subtitle: 'How to size bets to maximize long-run growth',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Kelly Criterion:</strong> The mathematically optimal bet size to maximize long-run compound growth. Bet too much = ruin. Bet too little = leave money on the table.</p>
<p>$$f^* = \\frac{bp - q}{b} = \\frac{p \\cdot b - (1-p)}{b}$$</p>
<p>Where: f* = fraction of bankroll, b = win/loss ratio, p = win probability, q = 1−p.</p>
<p><strong>Practical rule:</strong> Use half-Kelly or quarter-Kelly. Full Kelly is too aggressive for real trading — it assumes you know your exact edge, which you never do.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Example</h4><p>Win rate 60%, win $150, lose $100. b=1.5, p=0.6. f* = (1.5×0.6 − 0.4)/1.5 = <strong>0.33</strong>. Half-Kelly = 16.7%.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Max Position Rule</h4><p>Never risk more than 2-5% of capital on a single trade. This naturally approximates fractional Kelly.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Ruin Prevention</h4><p>Even with edge, bad sizing = ruin. The cemetery of traders is full of people who were right but sized wrong.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 6,
      title: 'Core Strategies',
      subtitle: 'The 4 vol-selling strategies that generate income',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p>All vol-selling strategies profit from <strong>theta decay + IV overstatement</strong>. You are the casino.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Short Straddle</h4><p>Sell ATM call + ATM put. Max profit = total premium. Wins if stock stays near strike. Highest theta, highest gamma risk.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Short Strangle</h4><p>Sell OTM call + OTM put. Wider breakevens than straddle. Lower premium but higher probability of profit.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Iron Condor</h4><p>Strangle + protective wings. Defined risk. Lower return but capped max loss. Best for capital-constrained accounts.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Calendar Spread</h4><p>Sell near-term, buy same-strike further out. Profits from near-term theta decay being faster. Works best in low-vol.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Trade Selection Checklist</h4><p>✓ IV Rank > 50% · ✓ VRP positive · ✓ No earnings within DTE · ✓ Size ≤ 2-5% of capital · ✓ Define exit rules BEFORE entry</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 7,
      title: 'Risk Management — VaR & Drawdown',
      subtitle: 'Survival first, profits second',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Value at Risk (VaR):</strong> The maximum expected loss over a given time period at a given confidence level.</p>
<p>$$\\text{VaR}_{95\\%} = \\mu - 1.645\\sigma \\quad \\text{(parametric, 1-day)}$$</p>
<p><strong>Max Drawdown:</strong> The largest peak-to-trough decline. Your real risk metric. A 50% drawdown requires a 100% gain to recover.</p>
<p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> If your strategy can lose more than 20% in a month, your sizing is too large. Period.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Correlation Kills</h4><p>10 "uncorrelated" positions become 1 position in a crash. Always stress-test for correlation spikes.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Tail Hedging</h4><p>Spend 1-2% of premium income on deep OTM puts. Insurance against the event that kills your strategy.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>The Survival Equation</h4><p>Edge × Volume − Costs − Ruin Probability = Career P&L. If ruin probability > 0, everything else is irrelevant.</p></div>
</div>`
    },
    {
      num: 8,
      title: 'Bayes\' Theorem',
      subtitle: 'Update beliefs with new evidence — the quant trader mindset',
      body: `
<div class="prose">
<p><strong>Bayes:</strong> How to update probabilities when you get new information. This is how you should think about every market signal.</p>
<p>$$P(A|B) = \\frac{P(B|A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)}$$</p>
<p><strong>Trading application:</strong> You start with a prior (e.g., "60% chance this stock stays in range"). New info arrives (earnings miss, Fed hike). Bayes tells you exactly how to update your probability — and therefore your position.</p>
</div>
<div class="ess-cheat-grid">
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Prior → Posterior</h4><p>Prior belief + new evidence = updated belief. Never anchor to your first estimate — always update.</p></div>
  <div class="ess-cheat-card"><h4>Poker Parallel</h4><p>Hand ranges narrow as cards are dealt. Preflop: wide range. After the flop: updated range. Bayes on every street.</p></div>
</div>`
    }
  ];

  let html = '';
  sections.forEach((s, idx) => {
    html += '<div class="ess-section' + (idx === 0 ? ' open' : '') + '" id="ess-' + s.num + '">';
    html += '<div class="ess-section-header" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle(\'open\')">';
    html += '<div class="ess-section-num">' + s.num + '</div>';
    html += '<div style="flex:1"><div class="ess-section-title">' + s.title + '</div>';
    html += '<div class="ess-section-subtitle">' + s.subtitle + '</div></div>';
    html += '<span class="ess-section-expand">▾</span></div>';
    html += '<div class="ess-section-body">' + s.body + '</div>';
    html += '</div>';
  });
  document.getElementById('essentials-content').innerHTML = html;

  // Render math
  if (window.renderMathInElement) {
    setTimeout(() => renderMathInElement(document.getElementById('view-essentials'), {
      delimiters: [{left:'$$',right:'$$',display:true},{left:'$',right:'$',display:false}]
    }), 100);
  }
}

// ─── JOURNAL ─────────────────────────────────────────────
function getJournal() {
  return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('qm_journal') || '[]');
}
function saveJournal(j) {
  localStorage.setItem('qm_journal', JSON.stringify(j));
}

function addJournalEntry() {
  const entry = {
    id: Date.now(),
    date: document.getElementById('j-date').value,
    ticker: document.getElementById('j-ticker').value,
    strategy: document.getElementById('j-strategy').value,
    thesis: document.getElementById('j-thesis').value,
    ivr: document.getElementById('j-ivr').value,
    entry: parseFloat(document.getElementById('j-entry').value) || 0,
    exit: parseFloat(document.getElementById('j-exit').value) || 0,
    qty: parseInt(document.getElementById('j-qty').value) || 1,
    lesson: document.getElementById('j-lesson').value
  };
  if (!entry.date || !entry.ticker) return alert('Date and Ticker are required');
  entry.pnl = (entry.entry - entry.exit) * entry.qty * 100; // options are ×100

  const j = getJournal();
  j.unshift(entry);
  saveJournal(j);
  renderJournal();

  // Clear form
  ['j-date','j-ticker','j-thesis','j-ivr','j-entry','j-exit','j-qty','j-lesson'].forEach(id => {
    document.getElementById(id).value = '';
  });
}

function deleteJournalEntry(id) {
  const j = getJournal().filter(e => e.id !== id);
  saveJournal(j);
  renderJournal();
}

function renderJournal() {
  const j = getJournal();
  let wins = 0, losses = 0, totalPnl = 0;
  let tbody = '';

  j.forEach(e => {
    const isWin = e.pnl >= 0;
    if (isWin) wins++; else losses++;
    totalPnl += e.pnl;
    tbody += '<tr class="' + (isWin ? 'j-win' : 'j-loss') + '">';
    tbody += '<td>' + e.date + '</td><td>' + e.ticker + '</td><td>' + e.strategy + '</td>';
    tbody += '<td>' + e.ivr + '%</td><td>$' + e.entry.toFixed(2) + '</td><td>$' + e.exit.toFixed(2) + '</td>';
    tbody += '<td>' + (isWin?'+':'') + '$' + e.pnl.toFixed(0) + '</td>';
    tbody += '<td>' + (isWin?'WIN':'LOSS') + '</td>';
    tbody += '<td style="max-width:200px;font-size:.78rem;color:var(--muted)">' + (e.lesson||'') + '</td>';
    tbody += '<td><button class="j-del-btn" onclick="deleteJournalEntry(' + e.id + ')">✕</button></td></tr>';
  });

  document.getElementById('journal-tbody').innerHTML = tbody;

  const wr = j.length > 0 ? Math.round(wins / j.length * 100) : 0;
  document.getElementById('journal-stats').innerHTML =
    '<div class="jstat-chip chip-blue"><div class="jchip-num">' + j.length + '</div><div class="jchip-lbl">Trades</div></div>' +
    '<div class="jstat-chip chip-green"><div class="jchip-num">' + wins + '</div><div class="jchip-lbl">Wins</div></div>' +
    '<div class="jstat-chip chip-red"><div class="jchip-num">' + losses + '</div><div class="jchip-lbl">Losses</div></div>' +
    '<div class="jstat-chip chip-gold"><div class="jchip-num">' + wr + '%</div><div class="jchip-lbl">Win Rate</div></div>' +
    '<div class="jstat-chip ' + (totalPnl >= 0 ? 'chip-green' : 'chip-red') + '"><div class="jchip-num">' + (totalPnl>=0?'+':'') + '$' + totalPnl.toFixed(0) + '</div><div class="jchip-lbl">Total P&L</div></div>';
}

// ─── INIT ────────────────────────────────────────────────
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  initDarkMode();
  // Show correct shortcut key for platform
  if (navigator.platform.indexOf('Win') > -1 || navigator.platform.indexOf('Linux') > -1) {
    const kbd = document.getElementById('search-kbd');
    if (kbd) kbd.textContent = 'Ctrl K';
  }
  setTrack(currentTrack);
  renderHome();
  renderJournal();
  updateProgress();
  updateActiveSidebarLink('home');

  // Global keyboard shortcuts
  document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
    // Search overlay keyboard handling
    const searchOpen = document.getElementById('search-overlay').style.display === 'flex';
    if (searchOpen) {
      if (e.key === 'Escape') { e.preventDefault(); closeSearch(); return; }
      if (e.key === 'ArrowDown') { e.preventDefault(); navigateSearchResults(1); return; }
      if (e.key === 'ArrowUp') { e.preventDefault(); navigateSearchResults(-1); return; }
      if (e.key === 'Enter') { e.preventDefault(); confirmSearchResult(); return; }
      return; // Don't process other shortcuts while search is open
    }

    // Quiz overlay — let it handle its own events
    if (document.getElementById('quiz-overlay').style.display === 'flex') {
      if (e.key === 'Escape') { closeQuiz(); return; }
      return;
    }

    // Cmd+K / Ctrl+K — open search
    if ((e.metaKey || e.ctrlKey) && e.key === 'k') {
      e.preventDefault();
      openSearch();
      return;
    }

    // / — also opens search (like GitHub, Slack)
    if (e.key === '/' && e.target.tagName !== 'INPUT' && e.target.tagName !== 'TEXTAREA') {
      e.preventDefault();
      openSearch();
      return;
    }

    // Escape — go home from any view
    if (e.key === 'Escape') {
      showView('home');
      return;
    }

    // Don't intercept if user is typing in an input/textarea
    if (e.target.tagName === 'INPUT' || e.target.tagName === 'TEXTAREA' || e.target.tagName === 'SELECT') return;

    const lessonView = document.getElementById('view-lesson');
    const inLesson = lessonView && lessonView.classList.contains('active');

    if (inLesson) {
      // Arrow keys / j,k for prev/next day
      if (e.key === 'ArrowLeft' || e.key === 'j') navigateDay(-1);
      if (e.key === 'ArrowRight' || e.key === 'k') navigateDay(1);
      // Space to toggle complete
      if (e.key === ' ') { e.preventDefault(); toggleComplete(); }
    }
  });
});
